Emu farming is a lucrative, low-labor commercial enterprise involving the breeding and raising of emus (large, flightless birds native to Australia) for their highly valuable meat, oil, skin, feathers, and eggs. Known for high adaptability to various climates, these birds require minimal, secure land—roughly 400–500 sq. ft. per bird—and are typically reared in pairs or groups, with 96% of the bird being usable.
